{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dd888abb-0b7d-40b4-82ac-8d279c969cb1","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest tool for .NET-specific CPU profiling.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper analysis, ETW events, GC/threading details |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | System-wide traces beyond just .NET |\n\n### Tip for high-CPU triage:\nRun `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first — check if `% Time in GC` is high. If so, the problem is memory pressure, not CPU-bound code, which changes your investigation path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"74639d85-f792-41b2-b0c1-2db32e180cd1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":346},"id":"9aaad5f4-46bb-40f7-a68b-a1270d03f983","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:52:19.293Z","parentId":"bd637096-240b-4cdb-8b79-eb2a542a9802"}
